snippet.textDisplay: It's weird. In most video games, i always have the feeling that i know i'll win, i know i'll save the world, because i'm the good guy and that's what i have to do. But this game sort of hit me differently. Throughout the whole thing, there's this whole theme that no matter what you do, the moon's always gonna crash in the end. You can't save anyone, you can only rewind time and start over again. It's just so hopeless, and i really wasn't used to video games doing that before i played this.

It's actually amazing how many important life lessons games like Zelda taught us. Look forward and fight, even if everything seems hopeless. Never give up, there will always be a new dawn. Someone will always be waiting for you. No matter how small you are, you can still be a hero. Link gives me courage every day of my life. Hope you found a better job and everything is a lot better now! Cheers

When I listen to this, I find my body goes very still and I begin to get a shiver that runs from the top of my head right down to the tips of my toes.

I always found this piece of music very moving and would always get Link to run the entire way from where ever he was to the clock tower. As I got closer clambering to reach the top of the clock tower, bells would ring and the earth shook violently. And when I reached the top, I would stare into the gaping abyss. Damn, this game was atmospheric!

snippet.textDisplay: @godverdegodverdomme I've played all 3, and OoT was better than both. LttP gave a loose story of an evil wizard getting the Triforce and warping the land to reflect his heart, but OoT made the overall experience much more immersive and enjoyable. It took the series in a new and fantastic direction while keeping true to the core feel of the series. MM had a good idea, but I hated it for stylistic reasons (that damn idiot moon) and the sheer uselessness of 80% of your masks.
snippet.textOriginal: @godverdegodverdomme I've played all 3, and OoT was better than both. LttP gave a loose story of an evil wizard getting the Triforce and warping the land to reflect his heart, but OoT made the overall experience much more immersive and enjoyable. It took the series in a new and fantastic direction while keeping true to the core feel of the series. MM had a good idea, but I hated it for stylistic reasons (that damn idiot moon) and the sheer uselessness of 80% of your masks.

snippet.textDisplay:
Oh as i sit and think with my bow this night, 
how i must overcome this terrible plight, 
the feelings that i have right now are stirred,
 the visions in my mind of friends so blurred,
dekus, gorons, zoras all alike,
i have helped them in their time of fright,
now ready i am with masks so true,
the feelings of many flow right through,
the moon is falling now it seems,
drawing near to my time of dreams,
fight him i know i must do, 
but after as ill leave, know that i will miss you

snippet.textDisplay:
Imagine walking through the lively town on the first day. People are laughing & dancing, peace reigns supreme. You happen to realize you just walked past a box you could've broken. So casually you turn around.
As you do the music fades quickly along with your turn & stops.
Everything except for you is in black & white and the town is empty, dead silent.
Everything is like this. You head to the Clock Tower, the arm comes down & the tower opens.
Skull Kid laughs. This plays.
Good atmosphere?

snippet.textDisplay: Thank you so much, SupraDarky, for finally adding this.
